<item>
            <title>[HBASE-4157] Possible performance improvement in Bytes.java</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-4157</link>
                <project id="12310753" key="HBASE">HBase</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;This is in line with the work already done on &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-4012&quot; title=&quot;Further optimize byte comparison methods&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-4012&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-4012&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It&apos;s possible to improve all functions like Bytes.toShort, Bytes.toInt... and Bytes.putShort, putInt... by calling sun.misc.Unsafe functions. However, when using these functions the endianess must be taken into account. Infortunatly, HBase uses big endian while x86 systems are little endian. Hence a conversion is required. This convertion (Integer.reverseBytes) is optimized on jdk1.7 and 1.6.u23 version (see jdk 6946040 &amp;amp; 2198024). So with 1.6.u23+, this improvement could bring something around 5-10% on the whole system. Moreover, as for &lt;a href=&quot;https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/HBASE-4012&quot; title=&quot;Further optimize byte comparison methods&quot; class=&quot;issue-link&quot; data-issue-key=&quot;HBASE-4012&quot;&gt;&lt;del&gt;HBASE-4012&lt;/del&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, a compatibility feature for non little endian cpus or jdk without sun.misc.unsafe will have to be kept.&lt;/p&gt;

</description>
